{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"28a55478-d15d-454e-966f-17bea333d61d","content":"Here's what I found:\n\n**`my_app/views.py:3`** — `datetime.now()`\n\n```python\nnow = datetime.now()\n```\n\nThis is a **hard-coded static call** that makes the function difficult to test because you can't control or predict the return value.\n\n### Recommended fix\n\nUse **`django.utils.timezone.now`** and inject it as a dependency:\n\n```python\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request, now_func=timezone.now):\n    now = now_func()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\nThis way, tests can pass a lambda or mock:\n\n```python\ndef test_index(rf):\n    fake_now = datetime(2026, 1, 1)\n    response = index(rf.get('/'), now_func=lambda: fake_now)\n```\n\n**Summary:** 1 untestable static found. Only one file (`views.py`) in the project, and it has a single `datetime.now()` call. Switching to an injectable `timezone.now` also fixes the common Django pitfall of naive (non-timezone-aware) datetimes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"17c1fbff-3093-4151-9572-424258c104c5","outputTokens":279,"requestId":"0BC8:1F2F04:65A6C3A:6EFDAD0:69F02052"},"id":"3855b369-f645-40ba-9dd6-9b7812813a22","timestamp":"2026-04-28T02:50:02.174Z","parentId":"3e700931-8b3e-4723-aa60-d0134c7dade1"}
